WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:02.440
I'm thrilled and delighted
to welcome you to the Library

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:04.570
of Congress National
Book Festival

00:00:04.570 --> 00:00:08.510
and to our fourth
annual Youth Poetry Slam.

00:00:08.510 --> 00:00:14.210
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:00:14.210 --> 00:00:19.570
This year we have
slammers from two teams

00:00:19.570 --> 00:00:22.480
who traveled quite long
distances to compete.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:23.930
So I'm going to announce them.

00:00:23.930 --> 00:00:26.770
Please join me in
welcoming, first,

00:00:26.770 --> 00:00:30.510
from somewhat nearby
Boston, Mass LEAP.

00:00:30.510 --> 00:00:36.050
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:00:36.050 --> 00:00:38.520
And from the other
coast in Sacramento,

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:41.510
the Sacramento Area
Youth Speaks.

00:00:41.510 --> 00:00:47.240
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:49.800
These two teams made
the final stage

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:54.510
of the 2018 Brave New Voices
International Youth Poetry

00:00:54.510 --> 00:00:57.510
Festival this last July.

00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:00.110
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:01:00.110 --> 00:01:04.250
And we are very happy to feature
representatives from both.

00:01:04.250 --> 00:01:07.000
We are also thankful
to Youth Speaks

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.370
and to their new
executive director,

00:01:09.370 --> 00:01:11.190
Christy Limon Johnston [sic],

00:01:11.190 --> 00:01:14.560
they are the organization behind
the festival, for their help

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:21.020
in bringing final stages
teams and poets to the slam.

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:24.360
I'm sorry to say that the
slammers from Dew More Poetry,

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:29.730
the 2018 Brave New Voices Slam
champions from nearby Baltimore,

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:31.720
were scheduled to be
here tonight, but,

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:33.760
unfortunately, had to cancel.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:37.550
But we do want to honor them
and their championship team,

00:01:37.550 --> 00:01:40.050
so we have a video from
this year's performance

00:01:40.050 --> 00:01:41.850
that we'd like to show.

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:45.150
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:51.570
&gt;&gt; [exhales loudly] Fatherhood
left my mother pregnant

00:01:51.570 --> 00:01:53.500
with absence.

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:57.610
&gt;&gt; Breastfed me broken promises.

00:01:57.610 --> 00:01:59.500
&gt;&gt; [in unison] My
father knows the neck

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:04.440
of liquor bottles better
than he knows my name.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:07.790
My Father loves his spirits just

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:11.460
like he loves being
one in my life.

00:02:11.460 --> 00:02:16.060
But now poetry has
been the best father

00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:18.540
since the biological one left.

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:21.490
&gt;&gt; Having an addict for a father
and a soldier for a mother,

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:24.420
the war on drugs will
happen on my homeland.

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:27.300
While she shot up people,
he shot up himself,

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:28.910
and I'm the one left for dead.

00:02:28.910 --> 00:02:30.890
&gt;&gt; Having a coffin for a mother

00:02:30.890 --> 00:02:33.000
and a criminal for
a sperm donor --

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.550
&gt;&gt; [in unison] You learn
to live outside the box.

00:02:35.550 --> 00:02:38.510
&gt;&gt; You become so
numb, like a robot.

00:02:38.510 --> 00:02:40.500
But how do you explain
to the world

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.590
that you have a barely
functioning motherboard?

00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:45.710
&gt;&gt; [in unison] And
then poetry came

00:02:45.710 --> 00:02:47.970
and raised me from
my broken home.

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:50.020
Words became magical.

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:52.730
Maybe that's why they
call it spelling.

00:02:52.730 --> 00:02:57.040
Through this American horror
story we coveted our pain.

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:00.930
But poetry taught us to
drop houses on our sorrows.

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:03.490
&gt;&gt; Meaning we used to
live in our depression --

00:03:03.490 --> 00:03:04.790
&gt;&gt; [in unison] Now we fight it.

00:03:04.790 --> 00:03:07.540
Boxed out my black out
for the title champion.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:10.660
&gt;&gt; All the times he told me I
wasn't man enough blaming the

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:12.790
women in my life
for my female traits

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:14.510
&gt;&gt; [in unison] He liked
to talk with his fists,

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:16.850
but got mad when I
talk with my hands.

00:03:16.850 --> 00:03:18.580
&gt;&gt; Only appears to appease.

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:21.300
Becomes a vanishing act
when it's time to raise.

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:22.600
&gt;&gt; Never taught me how to fight,

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:24.820
so I got jumped more
times the amount

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:27.070
of times I prayed
for you to save me.

00:03:27.070 --> 00:03:29.310
Changed my praying
hands into fists.

00:03:29.310 --> 00:03:31.480
&gt;&gt; [in unison] Became
my own guardian angel

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:35.960
when you had no more to give.

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:37.260
Dad, you are no savior.

00:03:37.260 --> 00:03:40.050
You just think you're God.

00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:44.590
That's why we can't
see or hear you.

00:03:44.590 --> 00:03:51.770
And our family forces
us to praise you.

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:54.310
&gt;&gt; I remember when
my mother died.

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:57.630
I couldn't tell which
was more cold --

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:00.870
my mother's or my father's
shoulder, or my mother's body.

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:04.210
I just didn't want to lose
all this joy in the morning.

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:07.520
But --

00:04:07.520 --> 00:04:10.490
&gt;&gt; [in unison] And
there's always a but.

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:23.250
Poetry taught me commas in place
of periods, taught me resilient

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:31.560
in place of malecide,
taught me metaphors

00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:33.950
in place of self-mutilation.

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:35.250
And isn't that what it
means to be a father?

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:36.550
When I'm slammed, I'm not
doing it for the points,

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:37.850
I'm doing it for all the love.

00:04:37.850 --> 00:04:39.150
&gt;&gt; I remember when I
wrote my depression poem.

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:40.450
Four people told me I gave them
the strength to finish theirs.

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:41.750
&gt;&gt; I remember [inaudible]
me and [inaudible]

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:43.050
to perform our abortion poem.

00:04:43.050 --> 00:04:44.350
Our tears and smiles
was all I needed,

00:04:44.350 --> 00:04:45.650
after having a life sucked out
of me, only took three minutes

00:04:45.650 --> 00:04:46.950
to breathe it back in.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:48.250
&gt;&gt; [in unison] Meaning
we were fatherless,

00:04:48.250 --> 00:04:49.550
but now our poetry
family raises us.

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:50.850
If it takes a village,
then I got that.

00:04:50.850 --> 00:04:52.150
Fatherhood left my mother
pregnant with absence.

00:04:52.150 --> 00:04:53.450
Breastfed me broken promises.

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:55.250
But what's a deadbeat
dad to a self-love poem?

00:04:55.250 --> 00:05:03.040
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:05.710
&gt;&gt; Although we wish Baltimore
was here with us, we are happy

00:05:05.710 --> 00:05:10.650
to have our local slam team
and our hometown pride.

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:14.470
So as with every National Book
Festival Youth Poetry Slam,

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:18.370
we are excited to introduce
the D.C. Youth Poetry Slam team

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:19.670
members and the team.

00:05:19.670 --> 00:05:21.510
Please give it up for them.

00:05:21.510 --> 00:05:28.500
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:31.910
Before I turn things over
to our emcee, Joseph Green,

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:35.550
who's done this poetry slam
for the last three years,

00:05:35.550 --> 00:05:37.060
I'd like to say a few words

00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:40.020
about our slam partner,
Split This Rock.

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:41.810
It's hard to imagine
where poetry

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:44.780
across the country would be
today without the organization.

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:47.780
And, of course, the
organization would not exist

00:05:47.780 --> 00:05:49.690
without all the hard
work of co-founder

00:05:49.690 --> 00:05:52.510
and executive director,
Sarah Browning.

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:57.140
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:05:57.140 --> 00:06:00.240
After ten incredible years,
Sarah has decided it's time

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.500
to turn the reins
over to another leader

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:05.400
as she goes off and
studies poetry.

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:08.930
Sarah, you have been a
force of good in my life,

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:11.210
and in the lives
of so many others.

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:13.790
And you've wowed the
Librarian of Congress, too.

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:15.590
She's hoping to make
it here tonight

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:17.960
to catch a little bit
of the poetry slam.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:21.530
One of her first official acts
as the Librarian of Congress was

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:25.420
to come here and
be a judge in 2016.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:28.210
But she did give me a little
something to pass along to you.

00:06:28.210 --> 00:06:31.510
So if you could come
up onto the stage?

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:39.040
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:43.300
So Sara this is a
rare harD.C.over copy

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:46.610
of "American Journal:
Fifty Poems for Our Time."

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:49.530
This is Tracy K.
Smith's anthology

00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:53.560
that is just coming out, part
of her second term project,

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:58.760
signed by the Librarian herself
with great love and affection.

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:00.330
So thank you, Sarah.

00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:02.600
[ Applause ]

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:05.300
It was really my pleasure.

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:07.510
And now Joseph Green.

00:07:07.510 --> 00:07:27.240
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:29.040
&gt;&gt; Welcome.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:31.750
[ Laughter ]

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:34.010
You expected it to be
more exciting, I know.

00:07:34.010 --> 00:07:35.710
[ Laughter ]

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:41.510
Welcome to the Library of
Congress Youth Poetry Slam.

00:07:41.510 --> 00:07:45.440
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:07:45.440 --> 00:07:47.510
I invite you to make
some more noise.

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:56.520
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:59.010
Do you feel like you've
made enough noise?

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:00.310
[ Laughter ]

00:08:00.310 --> 00:08:02.970
I don't feel like you
made enough noise.

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:05.290
Let me put that in perspective.

00:08:05.290 --> 00:08:11.250
Today, as you just witnessed,
you are about to listen to some

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:14.270
of the most powerful
voices of a generation.

00:08:14.270 --> 00:08:18.990
Young people who have been given
a space and a stage and a pen

00:08:18.990 --> 00:08:21.130
to write down the story
that they already had,

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:25.900
but we too often do not listen
to, they're going to come

00:08:25.900 --> 00:08:30.770
up here, and something
miraculous is going to happen.

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:34.890
You're going to feel connection
without anybody touching you.

00:08:34.890 --> 00:08:41.820
There's going to be something
profound going on in this room.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:47.230
I was raised in the south during
the summer times, and I would go

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:48.980
to church with my grandma.

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:52.550
And they would sing,
better than I can sing,

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:55.340
because I can't sing, "Are
You Ready for a Miracle?"

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:59.160
And the church would sing
back, "Ready as I can be."

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:00.900
Are you ready for a miracle?

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:04.190
&gt;&gt; [multiple speakers]
Ready as I can be.

00:09:04.190 --> 00:09:11.510
&gt;&gt; Library of Congress Youth
Poetry Slam make some noise!

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:17.120
[ Cheering ]

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:21.510
That feels better, that feels
better, that feels better.

00:09:21.510 --> 00:09:24.180
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:28.080
Welcome. My name is Joseph Green

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:30.450
and I will be your
host this evening.

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:33.210
I have a co-host, who
will be sitting over here.

00:09:33.210 --> 00:09:36.760
She is the director of youth
programs at Split This Rock.

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:38.060
Her name is Chelsea.

00:09:38.060 --> 00:09:40.510
Everyone give Chelsea
a round of applause.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:43.370
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:46.520
We'll be talking back and
forth as the slam goes.

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:47.980
Chelsea, say "what's
up" to everybody.

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:49.280
&gt;&gt; What's up everybody?

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:50.580
[ Laughter ]

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:51.880
&gt;&gt; Just like that.

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:53.740
You can feel the
connection, right?

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:56.760
We've been practicing the
five minutes before the show.

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:58.610
We just decided to do this.

00:09:58.610 --> 00:10:00.130
It's going to be crazy.

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:02.820
Things that you guys need
to know about, this program,

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:05.070
as you heard, was brought to
you not only by the Library

00:10:05.070 --> 00:10:06.420
of Congress, but
by Split This Rock.

00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:08.190
And a couple of things
that you need to know

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:10.750
about Split This Rock, their
mission is to cultivate,

00:10:10.750 --> 00:10:12.990
teach and celebrate
poetry that bears witness

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:14.900
to injustice and
provokes change.

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:16.430
Now, I'm gonna say that
again, because it sounds

00:10:16.430 --> 00:10:17.730
like I just read off
a bunch of words.

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:19.910
But I want you to really
listen to what they do,

00:10:19.910 --> 00:10:22.550
and what is behind what
we're doing here today.

00:10:22.550 --> 00:10:25.130
Split This Rock's
mission is to cultivate,

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:28.530
teach and celebrate
poetry that bears witness

00:10:28.530 --> 00:10:30.950
to injustice and
provokes change.

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:34.370
I think that you all can agree
there are some injustices,

00:10:34.370 --> 00:10:37.510
and we need to provoke
some change.

00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:44.170
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:10:44.170 --> 00:10:46.250
They do a lot of things
at Split This Rock along

00:10:46.250 --> 00:10:47.550
with their youth programs.

00:10:47.550 --> 00:10:48.850
And as the evening goes by,

00:10:48.850 --> 00:10:50.420
I will tell you more
about what they do.

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:52.320
Now I'm going to tell
you why we're here.

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:55.510
Show of hands if you've ever
been to a poetry slam before.

00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:57.970
Oh, okay, good.

00:10:57.970 --> 00:11:00.620
Show hands of hands if you've
never been to a poetry slam.

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:02.330
Oh, that's gorgeous.

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:03.630
All right, awesome.

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:06.190
People who have been to
poetry slam, say "what's up"

00:11:06.190 --> 00:11:08.060
to the people ain't never
been to a poetry slam.

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:09.360
What's up?

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:10.660
What's good?

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:11.960
How you doing?

00:11:11.960 --> 00:11:13.260
Nice to have you here.

00:11:13.260 --> 00:11:14.560
This is what's gonna
happen today.

00:11:14.560 --> 00:11:17.880
We have six amazing performers
who are going to get up here

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:19.400
and share an original
piece of writing

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:20.700
that they wrote themselves.

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:22.000
All right?

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:23.890
There will be no
musical accompaniment,

00:11:23.890 --> 00:11:25.470
there will be no props.

00:11:25.470 --> 00:11:30.650
And, because this is at the
National Book Festival sponsored

00:11:30.650 --> 00:11:33.270
by -- brought to you by
the Library of Congress,

00:11:33.270 --> 00:11:37.410
the first poem that each one of
the young people reads has to be

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:39.540
about books or reading
or learning.

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:40.840
Something in that space.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:42.140
And then the second poem can be

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:43.690
about whatever they
want it to be about.

00:11:43.690 --> 00:11:45.230
So you're gonna hear two rounds.

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:47.680
That's 12 poems.

00:11:47.680 --> 00:11:48.980
Prepare yourselves.

00:11:48.980 --> 00:11:50.280
It's going to be amazing.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:54.750
Okay? Now, at a poetry slam
it is a competition, right?

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:56.780
So -- I know, right?

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:58.170
Competition, boo, competition.

00:11:58.170 --> 00:11:59.470
But it's fun.

00:11:59.470 --> 00:12:00.770
It's America.

00:12:00.770 --> 00:12:02.070
This is what we do.

00:12:02.070 --> 00:12:03.370
All right?

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:04.670
We take an art form
and we deep-fry it,

00:12:04.670 --> 00:12:05.970
and we bring it to the world.

00:12:05.970 --> 00:12:07.270
[ Laughter ]

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:09.220
And so -- it sounds like
I'm just throwing shade,

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:12.360
but I like fried chicken, so.

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:16.750
The fun part about what we do
is we have some judges here

00:12:16.750 --> 00:12:20.370
that will be scoring these
poems from zero to ten.

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:22.510
Zero being the most
magnificent -- excuse me.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:26.220
[ Laughter ]

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:29.390
Ah, hm. Zero being
-- it's been a while

00:12:29.390 --> 00:12:30.710
since I've hosted a slam.

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:34.780
Zero being a -- we'll
call it a bad poem, right?

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:36.080
I don't know -- I don't
know if you want --

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:38.060
how you call a poem
bad, but we'll just say

00:12:38.060 --> 00:12:39.750
that that poem probably
shouldn't have made it

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:41.050
to stage today.

00:12:41.050 --> 00:12:44.810
I'm pretty much guaranteeing you
195% ain't no zero poems gonna

00:12:44.810 --> 00:12:46.180
make it to the stage today.

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:48.230
Now, then there's a ten.

00:12:48.230 --> 00:12:53.750
Ten is simultaneous
profound lifting of spirit

00:12:53.750 --> 00:12:57.530
of every member of this audience
to another realm of space

00:12:57.530 --> 00:12:59.890
and time, understanding,
same time.

00:12:59.890 --> 00:13:01.900
Who knows the commercials where
they're little heads pop and,

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:03.370
like, the little
blue smoke comes up?

00:13:03.370 --> 00:13:05.360
