&gt;&gt; Whoo!

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:41.300
&gt;&gt; Adjust that mic!

00:19:41.300 --> 00:19:43.060
Take your stage!

00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:44.360
&gt;&gt; Come on, Carlynn!

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.610
&gt;&gt; Black girl ready!

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:47.910
&gt;&gt; They not ready.

00:19:47.910 --> 00:19:50.210
&gt;&gt; Yeah!

00:19:56.510 --> 00:20:01.280
[ Exhales Loudly ]

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:05.020
&gt;&gt; Dear Marvel, after your
installment of "Black Panther,"

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:09.790
may I suggest a follow-up
movie, a sequel, if you will.

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:13.640
The movie will be about a
superhero, magic, black chick.

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:17.380
We can call her Super
Blackgirl or Afrowoman.

00:20:17.380 --> 00:20:19.980
Yeah. Afrowoman.

00:20:19.980 --> 00:20:23.700
Drape her cape in royal
purple because she is a queen.

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:25.890
Crown of kinky curls
bestowed upon her.

00:20:25.890 --> 00:20:28.360
Let her rock afro
puffs or box braids.

00:20:28.360 --> 00:20:32.110
And let the movie's theme
music be gospel hymn meets

00:20:32.110 --> 00:20:33.410
Kendrick Lamar.

00:20:33.410 --> 00:20:37.070
She can be played by
Viola Davis or Taraji P.,

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:38.710
or any other black woman,

00:20:38.710 --> 00:20:41.610
because aren't we all
magic in our own way?

00:20:41.610 --> 00:20:43.240
Aren't we superheroes?

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:46.620
Watch as we give birth to a
world full of brown folks.

00:20:46.620 --> 00:20:48.480
Watch as white folk tremble

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:51.020
at this gentle giant
we call a black woman.

00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:54.360
Ain't a black woman
also food and tsunami

00:20:54.360 --> 00:20:55.710
and sweet innocence [inaudible].

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:58.230
Watch as we make the
moon magic out of dust.

00:20:58.230 --> 00:21:00.700
Watch as we turn our
tears into a ocean,

00:21:00.700 --> 00:21:02.630
into a well for him
to drink from.

00:21:02.630 --> 00:21:07.690
Watch as we give all parts of
ourselves and do not disappear.

00:21:07.690 --> 00:21:11.670
But we do know black
women disappear.

00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:16.120
Easy. Left no trace like
evaporated instant smoke.

00:21:16.120 --> 00:21:18.420
Ain't that proof that
a black woman is magic,

00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:21.640
that we feed the world, and
we're then abracadabra'd away?

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:23.620
Can't we at least
have a Marvel movie,

00:21:23.620 --> 00:21:26.770
or a day we don't fear our
children dying in front of us?

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:31.390
So give us a movie, Marvel, and
let it be called "Afrowoman."

00:21:31.390 --> 00:21:33.960
The movie supervillain
can be the personification

00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:38.760
of white supremacy, or
Becky with the good hair,

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:41.790
or an evil clone played
by Rachel Dolezal.

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:44.820
Afrowoman's powers include
reversing the bullets,

00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:48.100
giving birth to a
revolution of invisibility.

00:21:48.100 --> 00:21:50.770
Also, hypervisibility.

00:21:50.770 --> 00:21:53.840
The metaphor being that black
women are always ignored

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:55.140
or exploited.

00:21:55.140 --> 00:21:58.280
Her invisibility powers are
on a set of bangle bracelets.

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:00.760
The metaphor being that
black women can be heard,

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:04.470
but not seen, like screams
or ghosts or gunshots.

00:22:04.470 --> 00:22:08.640
And when Afrowoman
defeats the villain,

00:22:08.640 --> 00:22:12.650
because she will
defeat the villain,

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:15.550
for once, she will be the hero.

00:22:15.550 --> 00:22:17.870
For once, she will
not take second place

00:22:17.870 --> 00:22:20.160
to something whites
or masculine.

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:23.470
For once, the black woman wins.

00:22:23.470 --> 00:22:26.480
And at the end of the movie I
want a scene where she marches

00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:31.710
down the street, all bantu
knots and combat boots,

00:22:31.710 --> 00:22:35.850
and a million black
women march behind her.

00:22:35.850 --> 00:22:40.700
The metaphor being that behind
every great black woman is a

00:22:40.700 --> 00:22:44.040
thousand other great
black women.

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:48.810
The street ahead is
dark and unknown.

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:52.680
Afrowoman shines all
the light in the galaxy.

00:22:52.680 --> 00:23:00.630
And this will not be a metaphor
or an explanation for anything.

00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:05.510
After all, we all know
black women are magic.

00:23:05.510 --> 00:23:16.550
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:23:16.550 --> 00:23:18.910
&gt;&gt; Okay. Okay.

00:23:18.910 --> 00:23:20.710
Okay.

00:23:20.710 --> 00:23:31.150
[ Cheering and Applause ]

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:32.450
Y'all ready?

00:23:32.450 --> 00:23:33.750
&gt;&gt; [multiple speakers] Yeah.

00:23:33.750 --> 00:23:35.130
&gt;&gt; I want to make sure
that you're ready,

00:23:35.130 --> 00:23:39.130
because you might hear
some things this evening

00:23:39.130 --> 00:23:42.200
that might contrast
your world view.

00:23:42.200 --> 00:23:44.620
You might hear some
things this evening

00:23:44.620 --> 00:23:48.030
that make you question
or wonder.

00:23:48.030 --> 00:23:50.530
You might hear some
things this evening

00:23:50.530 --> 00:23:53.600
that make you want
to learn more.

00:23:53.600 --> 00:23:55.540
You might hear some things
this evening you completely

00:23:55.540 --> 00:23:57.380
disagree with.

00:23:57.380 --> 00:23:59.580
But that's why we're here.

00:23:59.580 --> 00:24:03.970
We're here to grow and build
community, to celebrate voices

00:24:03.970 --> 00:24:08.390
that are not celebrated on a
regular basis, and to make space

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:11.580
for all the voices, because
this stage and this world

00:24:11.580 --> 00:24:14.830
and this literature,
this spoken word,

00:24:14.830 --> 00:24:17.710
these poems that we do
have room for all of us,

00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:19.550
a vision of all of us.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:24.800
So I hope that you're
ready, because I get tired,

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:28.500
and then I'm like, "Oh, man,
I'm sleepy," dah, dah, dah, dah.

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:29.800
And then I hear the first poem,

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:32.010
and then I remember
why I'm here again.

00:24:32.010 --> 00:24:33.620
So I just wanted to make
sure that all of you were

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:35.120
in the same space that I was.

00:24:35.120 --> 00:24:37.640
Also, judges, that's the longest
amount of time I'm ever going

00:24:37.640 --> 00:24:39.760
to give you to do your scores.

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:42.880
Chelsea, are we ready with
the first set of scores?

00:24:42.880 --> 00:24:44.180
&gt;&gt; Yes, sir.

